  "text": "The STRUCTURE software was used to analyse the obtained genotypic results [CITATION_1] . This approach analyses differences in the distribution of genetic variation between populations using a Bayesian iterative algorithm by grouping samples that share similar patterns of variation. STRUCTURE assigns individuals to the group representing the best fit for the variation patterns found [CITATION_2] . According to the delta-K method, the most likely number of groups identified among the analysed accessions was six ( Table 3 ). The grouping was largely consistent with the previous analyses, with the F. arundinacea and Festuca-like cultivars grouping together, and the F. pratensis accessions clustering, as were the two L. perenne accessions. The Lolium-like accessions (FlL) were the most diverse, with two accessions ('Felopa' and 'Vetra') placed in the same group as 'Uva' (L. multiflorum) and 'Vaive' (F. rubra). One FlL accession was grouped separately ('Punia'), while the other FlL accessions grouped together.",
